---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'SSDI FAQ | ssdicalc.com';
const description = 'Frequently asked questions about Social Security Disability Insurance eligibility, benefits, and the application process.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>SSDI FAQ</h1>

  <h2>What is SSDI?</h2>
  <p>Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI) is a federal program that pays monthly benefits to workers who become disabled and can no longer work. It is funded through payroll taxes (FICA).</p>

  <h2>How do I qualify for SSDI?</h2>
  <p>You must: (1) have a medically determinable physical or mental impairment expected to last 12+ months or result in death; (2) be unable to do substantial gainful activity (SGA); and (3) have sufficient work credits.</p>

  <h2>What are work credits?</h2>
  <p>Work credits are earned based on your annual wages or self-employment income. In 2025, you earn one credit for each $1,730 earned, up to 4 credits per year. Most people need 40 credits (10 years of work), with 20 earned in the last 10 years. Younger workers may qualify with fewer credits.</p>

  <h2>How long does the SSDI application take?</h2>
  <p>Initial decisions take 3–6 months. Most initial applications are denied (about 67%). Reconsideration takes 3–5 months. Hearings before an ALJ take 12–24 months. The full process can take 2–3 years.</p>

  <h2>What is the 5-month waiting period?</h2>
  <p>SSDI benefits begin 5 months after your disability onset date. You will not receive benefits for the first 5 months of disability. Medicare coverage begins 24 months after your SSDI entitlement date.</p>

  <h2>Can I work while receiving SSDI?</h2>
  <p>You can work during a Trial Work Period (TWP) of 9 months without losing benefits. After the TWP, earning above the SGA limit ($1,620/month in 2025, $2,700 for blind individuals) generally ends benefits.</p>

  <h2>What is the difference between SSDI and SSI?</h2>
  <p>SSDI is based on work history and is available to disabled workers who have paid into Social Security. SSI (Supplemental Security Income) is need-based and available to disabled individuals with limited income and resources, regardless of work history.</p>
</BaseLayout>
